'''Canada Day''' ({{lang-fr|Fête du Canada}}), formerly [[Dominion Day]] ({{lang-fr|Le Jour de la Confédération}}), is [[Canada]]'s [[National Day|national day]], a [[Public holidays in Canada|federal statutory holiday]] celebrating the anniversary of the July 1, 1867, enactment of the [[British North America Acts#British North America Act, 1867|British North America Act]] (today called the [[Constitution Act, 1867]]), which united two British colonies and a province of the [[British Empire]] into a single country within the empire called Canada.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web| url=http://www1.canadiana.org/citm/themes/constitution/constitution13_e.html| title=Canada in the Making &gt; Constitutional History &gt; 1867–1931: Becoming a Nation| publisher=Canadiana| accessdate=July 1, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web| url=http://atlas.nrcan.gc.ca/auth/english/maps/historical/territorialevolution/1867/1| last=Department of Natural Resources| authorlink=Natural Resources Canada| title=Natural Resources Canada &gt; Atlas Home &gt; Explore Our Maps &gt; History &gt; Territorial Evolution &gt; Territorial Evolution, 1867| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=July 1, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book| last=Moore| first=Christopher | title=1867: How the Fathers Made a Deal| publisher=McClelland &amp; Stewart| year=1998| location=Toronto| pages=1, 215| url=http://books.google.com/?id=Xumx9T6CrcIC&amp;printsec=frontcover&amp;q| isbn=9780771060960}}&lt;/ref&gt; Canada Day observances take place throughout Canada as well as internationally.

==Commemoration==
Frequently referred to as &quot;Canada's birthday&quot;, particularly in the popular press,&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news| last=Panetta| first=Alexander | last2=Pedwell| first2=Terry| title=An unforgettable Canada Day, eh?| newspaper=Toronto Star| date=July 2, 2007| url=http://www.thestar.com/article/231568| accessdate=May 12, 2007| ref=harv| postscript=.}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news| title=Canada Day celebrations| newspaper=Toronto Star| date=June 29, 2007| url=http://www.thestar.com/article/230791| accessdate=May 12, 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news| last=Canwest News Service| title=Harper salutes international role in Canada Day address| newspaper=National Post| date=July 1, 2007| url=http://www.canada.com/nationalpost/story.html?id=1153724d-9877-48af-9608-adef9a42d9cf| accessdate=May 12, 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt; the occasion marks the joining of the [[British North America]]n colonies of [[Nova Scotia]], [[New Brunswick]], and the [[Province of Canada]] into a [[federation]] of four provinces (the Province of Canada being divided, in the process, into [[Ontario]] and [[Quebec]]) on July 1, 1867. Canada became a kingdom in its own right on that date,{{#tag:ref|Canadian representatives had actually requested the title ''Kingdom of Canada'' be granted, to &quot;fix the monarchical basis of the constitution,&quot; but the idea was vetoed by the [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|British Foreign Secretary]] at the time, [[Edward Stanley, 15th Earl of Derby|the Lord Stanley]], and the title ''[[Dominion]]'' was used in its place.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book| last=Colquhoun| first=A. H. U.| publication-date=2009| contribution=The Fathers of Confederation: A Chronicle of the Birth of the Dominion| editor-last=Wrong| editor-first=George M.| editor2-last=Langton| editor2-first=H. H.| title=The Chronicles of Canada| volume=III| page=60| publication-place=Tucson| publisher=Fireship Press| year=2009| url=http://books.google.com/?id=Qs6IKxQxUjsC&amp;printsec=frontcover&amp;q| isbn=9781934757512| accessdate=July 1, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; See [[Name of Canada#Adoption of Dominion|Name of Canada &gt; Adoption of Dominion]].|group=n|name=Kingdom}}&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web| url=http://www.saintjohn.nbcc.nb.ca/~HeritageSaintJohn/CorporateSeal/heraldry.htm| title=Heritage Saint John &amp;gt Canadian Heraldry| publisher=Heritage Resources of Saint John and New Brunswick Community College| accessdate=July 3, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web| url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/MonarchAndCommonwealth/Canada/Historyandpresentgovernment.aspx| last=The Royal Household| title=The Queen and the Commonwealth &gt; Queen and Canada &gt; History and present government| publisher=Queen's Printer| accessdate=July 3, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal| author=Department of Canadian Heritage| authorlink=Department of Canadian Heritage| title=The Crown in Canada| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| year=2005| page=7| url=http://dsp-psd.pwgsc.gc.ca/Collection/CH4-127-2003E.pdf| accessdate=July 3, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite document| last=Department of Canadian Heritage| url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/symbl/101/101-eng.pdf| authorlink=Department of Canadian Heritage| title=Canada: Symbols of Canada| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| page=3| accessdate=July 1, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; but the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|British Parliament]] kept limited rights of political control over the new country that were shed by stages over the years until the last vestiges were surrendered in 1982 when the [[Constitution Act, 1982|Constitution Act]] patriated the Canadian constitution.{{#tag:ref|Among the powers retained by the Crown in its British Council was the power to declare war.|group=n|name=Powers}}

Under the federal Holidays Act, Canada Day is observed on July 1 unless that date falls on a Sunday, in which case July 2 is the statutory holiday, although celebratory events generally take place on July 1 even though it is not the legal holiday.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web| url=http://www.gov.sk.ca/news?newsId=b3903533-2a8d-40d7-8bc9-d718d9fd9367| last=Government of Saskatchewan| title=Canada Day to be observed Monday, July 2| date=June 18, 2007| publisher=Queen's Printer for Saskatchewan| accessdate=January 23, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; If it falls on a Saturday, the following Monday is generally also a day off for those businesses ordinarily closed on Saturdays.

==History==
[[File:Jubilee celebrations on Parliament Hill.jpg|thumb|right|Crowds on [[Parliament Hill]] celebrate [[Dominion Day]], 1927, the 60th jubilee of confederation]]
On June 20, 1868, [[Governor General of Canada|Governor General]] [[Charles Stanley Monck, 4th Viscount Monck|the Viscount Monck]] issued a royal [[proclamation]] asking for [[Canadians]] to &quot;celebrate the anniversary of the confederation.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web| url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/jfa-ha/canada-eng.cfm| last=Department of Canadian Heritage| authorlink=Department of Canadian Heritage| title=Ceremonial and Canadian Symbols Promotion &gt; Canada Day| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=July 1, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; However, the holiday was not established statutorily until 1879, when it was designated as [[Dominion Day]], in reference to the designation of the country as a ''[[Dominion]]'' in the British North America Act. The holiday was initially not dominant in the national calendar; up to the early 20th century, Canadians thought themselves to be primarily British, being thus less interested in celebrating distinctly Canadian forms of patriotism. No official celebrations were therefore held until 1917—the golden anniversary of Confederation—and then none again for a further decade.&lt;ref name=CanoeBkg&gt;{{cite news| last=Canadian Heritage| title=Canada Day Background/How we got our national holiday| publisher=Canoe| url=http://www.canoe.ca/Canadiana/canday.html| accessdate=July 1, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In 1946, [[Philéas Côté]], a Quebec member of the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]], introduced a [[private member's bill]] to rename Dominion Day as Canada Day.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news| last=Carnegie| first=R.K.| title=Drew Right: Provinces Have Say-So On Holidays| newspaper=The Globe and Mail| page=15| date=April 19, 1946| ref=harv| postscript=.}}&lt;/ref&gt; His bill was passed quickly by the House of Commons but was stalled by the [[Senate of Canada|Senate]], which returned the bill to the Commons with the recommendation that the holiday be renamed ''The National Holiday of Canada'', an amendment that effectively killed the bill.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news| last=Editorial Board| title=A New Low in Compromise| newspaper=The Globe and Mail| page=6| date=August 10, 1946}}&lt;/ref&gt;
[[File:Barrie Canada Day Fireworks.png|thumb|left|Canada Day fireworks in [[Barrie]], Ontario]]

Beginning in 1958, the Canadian government began to orchestrate Dominion Day celebrations, usually consisting of [[Trooping the Colour]] ceremonies on [[Parliament Hill]] in the afternoon and evening, followed by a mass band concert and fireworks display. [[Canadian Centennial|Canada's centennial]] in 1967 is often seen as an important milestone in the history of Canadian patriotism, and in Canada's maturing as a distinct, independent country, after which Dominion Day became more popular with average Canadians. Into the late 1960s, nationally televised, multi-cultural concerts held in [[Ottawa]] were added, and the fête became known as ''Festival Canada''; after 1980 the Canadian government began to promote the celebrating of Dominion Day beyond the national capital, giving grants and aid to cities across the country to help fund local activities.

With only twelve Members of Parliament present, eight less than a [[quorum]],&lt;ref name=Quorum&gt;{{Cite book| last=Marleau| first=Robert| last2=Montpetit| first2=Camille| title=House of Commons Procedure and Practice| place=Ottawa| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| date=January 2000| url=http://www2.parl.gc.ca/MarleauMontpetit/DocumentViewer.aspx?Sec=Ch09&amp;Seq=3&amp;Lang=E| chapter=9. Sittings of the House| accessdate=June 1, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; the private member's bill that proposed to change the name to Canada Day was passed in the House of Commons in five minutes, without debate.&lt;ref name=CBC&gt;{{cite web| url=http://archives.cbc.ca/society/celebrations//topics/2328/| title=Society &gt; Celebrations &gt; Celebrating Canada Day| publisher=CBC| accessdate=July 1, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; With the granting of [[Royal Assent]], the name was officially changed to Canada Day on October 27, 1982, a move largely inspired by the adoption of the [[Canada Act, 1982|Canada Act]], earlier in the year. Although the proposal caused some controversy,&lt;ref name=CBC /&gt; many Canadians had already been informally referring to the holiday as ''Canada Day'' for a number of years before the official name change occurred.{{#tag:ref|Numerous references to the term ''Canada Day'' may be found in issues of ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' published in the late 1970s.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news| title=Across Canada/Pro-Canada sign painter has brush with law| newspaper=The Globe and Mail| page=12| date=November 19, 1977| ref=harv| postscript=.}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news| last=Cherry| first=Zena| title=Protocol chiefs gather to discuss their trade| newspaper=The Globe and Mail| page=27| date=February 20, 1978}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news| last=Stevens| first=Geoffrey| title=With many tongues| newspaper=The Globe and Mail| page=6| date=March 2, 1978}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news| last=Canadian Press| title=Federal support for new festival| newspaper=The Globe and Mail| page=16| date=March 30, 1978}}&lt;/ref&gt;|group=n|name=Name}} Columnist Andrew Cohen called ''Canada Day'' a term of &quot;crushing banality&quot; and criticized the change from ''Dominion Day'' as being &quot;a renunciation of the past [and] a misreading of history, laden with political correctness and historical ignorance.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book| last=Andrew| first=Cohen| title=The Unfinished Canadian| publisher=McClelland &amp; Stewart| year=2007| location=Toronto| page=90| url=http://books.google.com/?id=glcBcaMC6doC&amp;lpg=PP1&amp;dq=Andrew%2C%20Cohen%20(2007).%20The%20Unfinished%20Canadian.&amp;pg=PA90#v=onepage&amp;q=Andrew,%20Cohen%20(2007).%20The%20Unfinished%20Canadian.| isbn=978-0771022869| ref=CITEREF_Cohen_2007}}&lt;/ref&gt; For Cohen, the change is an example of systemic denial of Canadian history by the Canadian government.&lt;ref&gt;{{Harvnb| Cohen| 2007| p=89}}&lt;/ref&gt;

As the anniversary of Confederation, Dominion Day, and later Canada Day, was the date set for a number of important events, such as the first national radio network hookup by the Canadian National Railway (1927), the inauguration of the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]]'s cross-country [[television]] broadcast (1958), the flooding of the [[Saint Lawrence Seaway]] (1958), the first colour television transmission in Canada (1966), the inauguration of the [[Order of Canada]] (1967), and the establishment of &quot;[[O Canada]]&quot; as the country's [[national anthem]] (1980). Other events fell on the same day coincidentally, such as the [[first day on the Somme|first day of the Battle of the Somme]] in 1916—shortly after which [[Dominion of Newfoundland|Newfoundland]] recognized July 1 as [[Memorial Day (Newfoundland and Labrador)|Memorial Day]] to commemorate the [[Newfoundland Regiment]]'s heavy losses during the battle&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web| url=http://www.heritage.nf.ca/society/custom.html| last=Hiscock| first=Philip| title=Society and Culture &gt; Folklore and Traditional Culture &gt; Custom| publisher=Memorial University of Newfoundland| accessdate=June 18, 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web| url=http://www.mun.ca/memorial/living/memorial_day.php| title=A Living Memorial &gt; Memorial Day| publisher=Memorial University of Newfoundland| accessdate=May 31, 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt;—and the enactment of the [[Chinese Immigration Act, 1923|Chinese Immigration Act]] in 1923—leading [[Chinese-Canadian]]s to refer to July 1 as ''Humiliation Day'' and boycott Dominion Day celebrations until the act was repealed in 1947.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news| title=CBC News &gt; Indepth &gt; China &gt; Chinese Immigration| publisher=CBC| date=June 10, 2004| url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/background/china/chinese_immigration.html| accessdate=July 1, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Activities==
[[File:Canada Day 2008 Snowbirds over Parliament.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Snowbirds]] on Canada Day celebrations in [[Ottawa]]]]
[[Image:EIIR-Chretien.jpg|thumb|right|[[Elizabeth II]], [[Monarchy of Canada|Queen of Canada]], and the then-[[Prime Minister of Canada]], [[Jean Chrétien]], at the official Canada Day celebration in Ottawa, 1997]]

Most communities across the country will host organized celebrations for Canada Day, usually outdoor public events, such as parades, carnivals, festivals, barbecues, air and maritime shows, fireworks, and free musical concerts,&lt;ref name=Heritage96&gt;{{cite web| url=http://www.canadianheritage.gc.ca/newsroom/index_e.cfm?fuseaction=displayDocument&amp;DocIDCd=6NR110| last=Department of Canadian Heritage| authorlink=Department of Canadian Heritage| title=British Columbia and Yukon invited to participate to &quot;Celebrate Canada!&quot; Days| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=May 31, 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt; as well as [[Oath of Citizenship (Canada)|citizenship ceremonies]] for new citizens.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web| url=http://www.cic.gc.ca/English/citizenship/cit-ceremony.asp| last=Citizenship and Immigration Canada| authorlink=Citizenship and Immigration Canada| title=Applying for citizenship &gt; The citizenship ceremony| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=July 1, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web| url=http://www.rsscanadaimmigration.com/en/citizenship/citizenshipoath.php| title=Canadian Citizenship Oath| publisher=Robinson Sheppard Shapiro| accessdate=July 1, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; There is no standard mode of celebration for Canada Day; professor of International Relations at the [[University of Oxford]] [[Jennifer Welsh]] said of this: &quot;Canada Day, like the country, is endlessly decentralized. There doesn't seem to be a central recipe for how to celebrate it—chalk it up to the nature of the federation.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news| last=Allemang| first=John| title=We stand on guard for what?| newspaper=Globe and Mail| date=June 28, 2008| url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20080627.wcandayfocusdebate/BNStory/CanadaDay2008/?pageRequested=all| accessdate=July 1, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; However, the locus of the celebrations is the national [[Capital (political)|capital]], [[Ottawa]], [[Ontario]], where large concerts, presided over by the governor general, are held on [[Parliament Hill]], as well as other parks around the city and in [[Hull, Quebec]]. The [[Monarchy of Canada|sovereign]] may also be in attendance at Canada Day celebrations in Ottawa; Queen [[Elizabeth II]] was present in 1990, 1992, 1997,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web| url=http://www.crht.ca/DiscoverMonarchyFiles/QueenElizabethII.html| last=Bousfield| first=Arthur| last2=Toffoli| first2=Garry | title=Elizabeth II Queen of Canada: The Role of Queen Elizabeth II| publisher=Canadian Royal Heritage Trust| accessdate=May 31, 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt; and 2010,&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite press release| title=The Queen to address the United Nations| publisher=Queen's Printer| date=January 22, 2010| url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/LatestNewsandDiary/Pressreleases/2010/TheQueentoaddresstheUnitedNations.aspx| accessdate=January 23, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; when more than 100,000 people attended the ceremonies on Parliament Hill.&lt;ref name=StarW&amp;K&gt;{{Citation| last=Campion-Smith| first=Bruce| title=Royal newlyweds are coming to Canada, but not Toronto| newspaper=Toronto Star| date=February 16, 2011| url=http://www.thestar.com/news/canada/article/939727--royal-newlyweds-are-coming-to-canada-but-not-toronto?bn=1| accessdate=February 16, 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news| title=Queen calls Canada 'example to the world'| publisher=CBC| date=July 1, 2010| url=http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2010/07/01/canada-day001.html| accessdate=February 16, 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt; The Queen also helped celebrate Canada's 100th anniversary on July 1, 1967.&lt;ref name=CanoeBkg /&gt;  [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge|Prince William]] and [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge|his wife]] are expected to be present on Canada Day, 2011.&lt;ref name=StarW&amp;K /&gt;

Given the federal nature of the holiday, celebrating Canada Day can be a cause of friction in the province of [[Quebec]], where the holiday is overshadowed by Quebec's [[National Holiday (Quebec)|National Holiday]], on June 24.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news| last=Fedio| first=Chloe| title=Canada Day Parade organizers bemoan lack of political support| newspaper=The Gazette| date=June 17, 2010| url=http://www.montrealgazette.com/health/Canada+Parade+organizers+bemoan+lack+political+support/3164763/story.html| accessdate=July 1, 2010}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}&lt;/ref&gt; For example, the federal government funds events at the [[Old Port of Montreal]]—an area run by a federal [[Crown corporations of Canada|Crown corporation]]—while the parade is a [[grassroots]] effort that has been met with pressure to cease, even from federal officials.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news| last=Hustake| first=Aalan| title=Proud Canadian, proud Quebecer who loved a parade| newspaper=The Gazette| date=May 25, 2008| url=http://www.canada.com/montrealgazette/news/insight/story.html?id=069c09a6-3deb-4246-8e2e-a7d5324b8b26| accessdate=May 25, 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt; The nature of the event has also been met with criticism from [[English Canadian]]s, such as ''[[Ottawa Citizen]]'' columnist [[David Warren (columnist)|David Warren]], who said in 2007: &quot;The Canada of the government-funded paper flag-waving and painted faces—the 'new' Canada that is celebrated each year on what is now called 'Canada Day'—has nothing controversially Canadian about it. You could wave a different flag, and choose another face paint, and nothing would be lost.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news| last=Warren| first=David| author-link=David Warren (columnist)| title=Sea to sea| newspaper=Ottawa Citizen| date=July 1, 2007| url=http://www.davidwarrenonline.com/index.php?id=750}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Canada Day also coincides with Quebec's traditional [[Moving Day (Quebec)|Moving Day]], when many fixed-lease apartment rental terms expire. The bill changing the province's moving day from May 1 to July 1 was introduced by a federalist member of the [[National Assembly of Quebec|Quebec National Assembly]], [[Jérôme Choquette]],&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news| last=Lejtenyi| first=Patrick| title=Moving day conspiracy| newspaper=Montreal Mirror| url=http://www.montrealmirror.com/ARCHIVES/2002/070402/ncity.html| accessdate=July 1, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; in order not to affect children still in school in the month of May.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news| last=Madigan| first=Tracey| url=http://www.cbc.ca/montreal/features/movingday/| title=Get a Move On| date=June 28, 2005| publisher=CBC| accessdate=July 1, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

===International celebrations===
[[File:A game of Canadian street hockey on Trafalgar Square.jpg|thumb|left|[[Street hockey]] on [[Trafalgar Square]], in front of the [[National Gallery]], for Canada Day in [[London]], [[England]]]]
Canadian [[expatriate]]s will organize Canada Day activities in their local area on or near the date of the holiday. For instance, since 2006, annual Canada Day celebrations have been held at [[Trafalgar Square]]—the location of [[Canada House]]—in [[London]], [[England]]; organized by the Canadian community in the United Kingdom and the [[High Commission of Canada in London|Canadian High Commission]], the event features Canadian performers and a demonstration of [[Street Hockey|street hockey]], amongst other activities.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web| url=http://www.canadadaylondon.com/default.asp| last=The Canadian High Commission in London| title=Canada Day in London| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=July 1 , 2009}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}&lt;/ref&gt; Annual celebrations also take place in [[Hong Kong]], entitled ''Canada D'eh'' and held on June 30 at ''[[Lan Kwai Fong]]'', where an estimated attendance of 12,000 was reported in 2008; in [[Afghanistan]], where members of the [[Canadian Forces]] mark the holiday at their base;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite press release| title=Afghanistan Canada Day Celebrations Video Footage Available on Website| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| date=June 29, 2006| url=http://www.forces.gc.ca/site/news-nouvelles/view-news-afficher-nouvelles-eng.asp?id=1972| accessdate=July 1, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news| url=http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20060629/afghanistan_canadaday_060701/20060701?hub=TopStories| title=Troops refuse to let attack mar Canada Day break| date=July 1, 2006| publisher=CTV| accessdate=August 6, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; and in Mexico, at the American Legion in [[Chapala]] and the Canadian Club in [[Ajijic]].{{Citation needed|date=November 2009}} 

[[Detroit, Michigan]], and [[Windsor, Ontario]], have, since the 1950s, celebrated both Dominion or Canada Day and the United States' [[Independence Day (United States)|Independence Day]] with the [[Windsor-Detroit International Freedom Festival|International Freedom Festival]]. A massive fireworks display over the [[Detroit River]], the strait separating the two cities, is held annually with hundreds of thousands of spectators attending. A similar event occurs at the [[Friendship Festival]], a joint celebration between [[Fort Erie, Ontario]], and neighbouring [[Buffalo, New York]], of Canada Day and Independence Day.
{{-}}

